<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Luxury carmakers fight tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three leading European luxury carmakers - Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, and BMW -
have joined forces to seek European Commission action against the Italian
government to force changes in what they claim are discriminatory taxes on
large cars in the Italian market. Mr Nicholas Scheele, Jaguar's chairman, is
to meet Mrs Christiane Scrivener, commissioner for tax matters, in Brussels
today to press the companies' complaints which have the backing of both UK
and German governments. The carmakers claim five Italian taxes breach
European law and have undermined their sales of large cars while favouring
Italian manufacturers. The taxes introduced in 1992 and 1993 are based on
engine size, cars with engine capacity above two litres being penalised
particularly. All Jaguar cars have engines of more than two litres.
</TEXT>
