<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 94 / Albania jails Greek 'spies'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TIRANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Five ethnic Greeks were yesterday found guilty by an Albanian court of
spying for Greece and illegal possession of arms after a highly charged
trial that has raised tensions between Albania and Greece. The five men are
all leading members of Omonia, an Albanian political movement which
campaigns for the rights of the country's ethnic minority with close
co-operation and funds from Greece. They were convicted of collaboration
with the Greek intelligence service and encouraging secessionist activities
among the Greek minority in southern Albania. Greece tried unsuccessfully to
block the trial, claiming it was politically motivated and aimed at
discrediting Greek links with the minority. Since the case began on August
15, Greece has expelled more than 40,000 illegal Albanian immigrants and
blocked European Union aid to Albania worth Ecu35m (Pounds 27.5m) to try to
stop the trial. Before the verdict was announced a defence ministry
spokesman in Athens said military patrols along the border had been stepped
up to prevent the expelled Albanians returning. The Greek embassy in Tirana
said the verdict was 'a joke. No-one proved anything and the verdict was
simply a reading of the indictment'.
</TEXT>
