<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets: Brazil sees 3.8% rebound
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sao Paulo rebounded 3.8 per cent as a new opinion poll showed that Mr
Fernando Henrique Cardoso had retained his lead in the presidential race,
and might even win at the first round of voting on October 3.
The market had plunged by 10.5 per cent on Monday amid worries that Mr
Cardoso's candidature would be damaged in the wake of the resignation of Mr
Rubens Ricupero as the economy minister.
The Bovespa index ended 1,846 up at 49,886 after publication of the poll,
conducted after Mr Ricupero's resignation.
In New York, however, Goldman Sachs lowered its weighting in Brazilian
stocks to neutral from overweight, on the view that Mr Cardoso was unlikely
to succeed in the election in the first round, although it still expected
him to win the presidency.
The financial markets will be closed today as the country celebrates
Independence Day.
</TEXT>
