FT  07 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Peek profits show 57% rise to Pounds 3.26m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong performance from the field data systems division helped Peek, whose
principal business is traffic systems, to lift interim profits sharply.
They rose to Pounds 3.26m for the six months to June, from Pounds 2.07m in
the corresponding period last year, when there was a loss of Pounds 554,000
on the disposal of discontinued businesses.
Total group sales grew by 28 per cent, from Pounds 44.3m to Pounds 56.6m.
Mr Allen Standley, chief executive, said that the field data division had
benefited from improving markets and wider acceptance of the company's newer
products, including the Husky hand-held computer.
Net cash totalled Pounds 158,000 in the period, compared with net borrowings
of Pounds 1.9m in the year-earlier period. Interest payable was Pounds
11,000, compared with Pounds 194,000 received previously. Earnings per share
improved from 1.11p to 1.75p. The interim dividend is unchanged at 1.05p.
