<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Bowater expects further recovery: Raw material price rises
passed on to customers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bowater, the packaging and printing group, yesterday reported a recovery in
important markets and said higher raw materials prices were largely being
passed on to customers.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to June 30 rose 2 per cent from Pounds
103m to Pounds 105m - at the top end of expectations. Excluding exceptional
gains of Pounds 8m last year, and a loss on disposals of Pounds 4m this
year, the underlying increase was from Pounds 95m to Pounds 109m, a rise of
15 per cent.
Mr David Lyon, chief executive, said an upturn in demand in the US, UK and
some continental European markets had led to price rises for Bowater's main
raw materials - paper, and resin for plastics - of about 20 per cent between
April and June.
'We have generally been able to pass these increases on to customers,
although there are some timing delays,' Mr Lyon said.
He said raw materials prices were expected to increase by up to another 10
per cent by December, with shortages of some commodities forecast, although
prices remained about 25 per cent below their peak in the late 1980s. This
was likely to lead to a further year-on-year improvement in the second half.
The positive outlook - which contrasted strongly with Bowater's downbeat
assessment of future trends after last year's strong results - lifted
Bowater's shares 19p to 492p.
Mr Lyon said Bowater's acquisition of healthcare packaging manufacturers DRG
and Cope Allman in 1992, and of Specialty Coatings International last year,
had given it critical mass in several target markets with strong growth
opportunities.
Group turnover rose 14 per cent from Pounds 1.02bn to Pounds 1.16bn, with
the group operating margin up from 8.8 per cent to a record 9.2 per cent.
After a difficult second half last year, the packaging and print businesses
staged a recovery with sales up 3 per cent to Pounds 580.7m, and operating
profits of Pounds 49.8m against last year's Pounds 50.9m. Cosmetic packaging
performed well in the UK and continental Europe, but food packaging prices
remained under pressure from price competition among food retailers.
Healthcare packaging enjoyed 'buoyant' demand.
The acquisition of SCI greatly increased the contribution from Bowater's
coated products division, with sales up from Pounds 194.2m to Pounds 280.3m,
and operating profits from Pounds 22.5m to Pounds 32.7m.
Both sales and profits also increased in Bowater's building and engineering
businesses, and its tissue business in Australia.
Earnings per share, including exceptional items, increased from 12.3p to
14.2p, and the interim dividend is raised by 9 per cent from 5.3p to 5.8p.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
