<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's Short Stories documentary is about nutty enthusiasts, almost
invariably surefire material for television. Until two years ago, Swansea
Aero Club was run by the local council. Then money problems brought the
threat of closure and a group of flying enthusiasts decided to buy it and
run it as a private company (8.30 C4). Witness is another C4 documentary,
this time about Boris Zolotov, a Russian who runs four-week seminars and, we
are assured, uses his telepathic powers to bring rooms full of people to
orgasm. Jolly useful (9.00). Michael Gambon, Susannah Harker, Connie Booth,
Gemma Jones, and many more, including Ken Livingstone as himself, appear in
Faith, a thriller wrapped around News At 10 today and tomorrow which
combines politicians' sex scandals and arms deals (9.00). William Ivory's
Common As Muck will inevitably be compared with 'The Dustbinmen', not just
because both are about dustmen but because the 1969 series was written by
Jack Rosenthal. That was a comedy of course, whereas the series starting on
BBC1 today is a six-part drama (9.30).
