<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Technology fails to impress bank customers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumers show a marked lack of enthusiasm for technological developments
such as home banking, and appear to prefer conventional banking methods,
says a a survey published yesterday.
Within the general level of caution, there was greater interest in
technological services from the under-35 age group.
The poll by Mori for computer company ICL, revealed that three-quarters of
those questioned would not use a home banking service if it was available.
One-third of respondents said they had never used a cashpoint machine.
The most popular single extra service which customers would like to be
available through cash machines is the sale of postage stamps.
The survey also shed light on consumers' views of financial institutions.
When consumers were asked which organisations other than banks or societies
they would trust to look after their money, 24 per cent said insurance
companies. There should be a single regulator for building societies and
banks, Mr Peter Birch, chief executive of Abbey National, the home loans and
banking group, said yesterday at a Chartered Institute of Bankers' seminar.
This might mean the Building Societies Commission becoming part of the
supervisory department of the Bank of England.
Consumers' Attitudes to Home Finance and Technology. ICL Financial Services,
International House, 292-298 High Street, Slough SL1 1NB. Pounds 10.
Byte of the new, Page 21
</TEXT>
