<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Leak reveals plan to axe post offices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office is planning cuts in its branch and sub-post offices in the
next five years, according to an internal document leaked yesterday by the
Union of Communication Workers.
Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, said the paper painted a
'worst-case scenario' that was unlikely to happen because of the
government's plans to give the corporation commercial freedom in the private
sector.
He said the document was prepared earlier in the year to show what would
happen if the Post Office did not achieve the commercial freedom it needed
to develop.
However the union said the document was drawn up in May and sent to Post
Office regional managers on August 15, two months after publication of the
government's consultative document.
Mr Cockburn said some rural sub-post offices were closing because they were
too small to run profitably, but added: 'The government's decision to allow
post offices to sell a wider range of services has secured the rural
network.' He pledged to help open 40 to 50 part-time rural post offices a
year.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, backed the Post Office
management's desire for commercial freedom in the private sector in a green
paper published before the summer break. It set out the government's
'preferred option' of a sale of 51 per cent of the Post Office. A further 10
per cent would go to employees and sub-postmasters.
The leaked forecast suggests branch or crown offices would have to be cut
from 717 in this financial year to 397 by 1998-1999 with a reduction in the
number of sub-post offices from 18,055 in this financial year to 17,005 by
the end of the decade.
The document says this would ensure Pounds 70m of savings in the next five
years. It forecasts a corresponding increase in the number of 'converted' or
franchised post offices from 800 to 1,180 in the same period.
The union said the figures were a 'recent projection of how the network will
shrink if the government's preferred option of break-up and privatisation
set out in the green paper on the postal services is introduced'.
Mr Cockburn said the document showed that there would be more post offices
in five years because of the increase in franchising, which had led to the
opening of post offices in supermarkets.
He said he would monitor carefully the future of post office franchising on
a 'case-by-case, community-by-community basis'.
</TEXT>
