<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Watchdog raps anti-nuclear ad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Advertising Standards Authority, the advertising watchdog, today accuses
Greenpeace, the environmental group, of 'gross over-simplification' and
'poor taste' in an anti-nuclear power advertisement in some national
newspapers earlier this year.
The advertisement featured a photograph of a baby with an enlarged head and
was captioned 'Kazakhstan nuclear test victim'.
The text claimed that radiation-linked diseases in children 'have already
been seen near to nuclear installations such as Sellafield' and that '2,000
will die because of the radioactive discharges from Sellafield over the next
10 years'.
The ruling published today said there was no proof that the baby was a
nuclear test victim, and the figure of 2,000 deaths had not been
substantiated. It also ruled that it was 'unfounded' to describe the nuclear
industry as 'intent on spreading radiation and the means of mass destruction
around the globe'.
However, the authority rejected complaints about the linking of the nuclear
industry and childhood diseases.
It stated: 'The authority sought expert advice and understood that, while
there were measurable excesses of childhood leukaemia and related cancers in
the vicinity of Sellafield and some other nuclear installations, a causal
link with the UK civil nuclear industry had not been established.'
'It considered, however, that this was a matter of public controversy and
that readers would therefore recognise, particularly given the advertiser's
identity, that this was an expression of the advertiser's opinion based on
the available evidence.'
The British Nuclear Industry Forum, the trade body, said the advertisement
had 'done much harm' as the the government is conducting a review of the
industry.
Greenpeace said it stood by the advertisement.
</TEXT>
