<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Blair refuses to back rail strike: TUC warms to works
councils - Union chiefs attacked on pit closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair yesterday refused to throw his support behind the rail signal
workers' strike in a move calculated to distance the party from industrial
conflicts.
He called on the government to free both sides - the RMT transport union and
Railtrack - to negotiate a settlement of the 13-week conflict. If this
failed it should go to arbitration under existing agreements for the railway
industry, Mr Blair said. The Labour leader said he had 'considerable
sympathy' for the justice of the signal workers' cause, but had to look at
the dispute from 'the public interest'.
However, Mr Blair's suggestion of arbitration has not found favour on either
side of the rail dispute. Both the RMT and Railtrack are strongly opposed.
Moreover his refusal to intervene on the side of the signal workers has
disappointed union leaders.
Mr Blair emphasised that politicians should not become involved in
industrial disputes. 'If I started intervening or interfering I would be
doing precisely what I have criticised the government for doing.'
There was widespread support for the RMT and its general secretary Mr Jimmy
Knapp at the TUC congress yesterday. He secured 1.6m votes in his first
election for the TUC general council in the smaller-union section.
A congress debate on the RMT strike will take place today. The TUC plans a
mass rally of support tomorrow, when the signal workers will be on strike
for 24 hours.
Mr Paul Gallagher, general secretary of the AEEU engineering and electrical
union and a member of the Health and Safety Commission, said he was calling
on the Health and Safety Executive to investigate the training of British
Rail staff who will be working in signal boxes on strike days.
Mr Gallagher said: 'I want to know how, after less than two weeks' training
or retraining, it is possible for Railtrack to say a person is competent to
work in a signal box when it takes nine months to train a signal worker.'
A growing number of train operating companies have stopped making automatic
ticket refunds to travellers affected by the dispute because of the
increased frequency of special strike-day services.
In some areas ticket staff have been making refunds to season ticket holders
in spite of the fact that travellers have been able to use the reduced
services on strike days.
BR said a decision on refunds was up to train operators. Rail users' groups
said refunds should still be paid on routes where services started late or
finished early.
</TEXT>
