<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Receivers to Swans say sale is remote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Price Waterhouse, the receivers to the Tyneside shipbuilder Swan Hunter,
said yesterday that the prospects of selling the yard were now remote, Chris
Tighe writes.
Mr Gordon Horsfield, joint receiver, said there were at this stage no
serious bidders. Price Waterhouse, he said, would now begin looking at
offers received for parts of the business, in parallel with any approaches
for the whole.
The receivers, he added, would try for a whole sale right up to the
departure of the Type 23 frigate Richmond, the last vessel on Swans' books,
on November 2.
Following Monday's collapse of hopes of a sale to Constructions Mecaniques
de Normandie, the receivers are considering a CMN proposal to sub-contract
work for some weeks to Swans' design team. Mr Horsfield said that, if
agreement could be reached within 48 hours, the Friday deadline for making
Swans' 100-strong design team redundant would be lifted.
It emerged yesterday that the Tyne and Wear Development Corporation, North
and South Tyneside and Newcastle councils and private-sector interests had
formulated a proposal, should no going-concern sale be possible, to acquire
Swans as a subsea oil and gas exploration and production base. The
initiative, costing around Pounds 20m, would require government support.
Organisation Management and Survey, a Manchester-based engineering
consultancy, also confirmed it was interested in buying Swans as a going
concern.
</TEXT>
