<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Consultation 'to be transformed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European Court judgments in June requiring UK employers to consult employee
representatives on redundancies and business transfers, even where they do
not recognise unions, could transform worker consultation in Britain, says a
TUC legal opinion.
Lord Wedderburn says companies will not be able to form committees for
consultation and then dissolve them at will. Vehicles for consultation will
require adequate resources and proper independence from the employer.
The government is wrestling with how to implement the judgment with the
least inconvenience to business.
The Wedderburn analysis is included in an interim report on representation
at work which was strongly supported by the congress yesterday.
The report takes another significant step to TUC acceptance of
Continental-style rights at work and works councils, but attempts to combine
that with an important role for union organisation.
The report says: 'This twin-track approach would give legal rights to
individuals and unions. At the workplace level all employees would have
rights to representation, rights to trigger arrangements for information and
consultation and rights to be a union member.'
It also spells out a staged process of union involvement from a right to
represent all workers in individual grievances to full union recognition for
collective bargaining.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union, introduced the
interim report. He reassured those suspicious of individual rights that the
proposals would not undermine union organisation.
He said: 'We cannot import a model from another country whose tradition of
industrial relations is different from ours. Neither can we say they have
nothing to teach us.'
Mr Tony Dubbins, general secretary of the GPMU print union, warned that
works councils might not be appropriate in smaller companies. 'It would be a
monumental own-goal if these new rights make it more difficult for unions to
organise,' he said.
The Confederation of British Industry was yesterday urged to reach agreement
on a European 'framework agreement' with unions which would provide for a
minimum of five days of vocational training each year.
</TEXT>
