<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Simpler payments to victims suggested
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes in the law to make it easier to pay damages in instalments to
victims of personal injury are recommended in a report published yesterday
by the Law Commission.
The commission, which advises the government on law reform, says changes are
needed that would allow insurers to buy annuities to make the payments
direct to the victim tax-free.
Many victims of accidents prefer the payment of some or all of the damages
in instalments. These structured settlements often involve a lump sum up
front, with payments for the rest of their lives.
The commission says regular payments offer victims greater certainty about
their financial future than a lump sum. Furthermore, they can be tailored to
the victim's needs.
The recommendations would allow the payments to be made direct to the
injured person, without deduction of tax. The insurer would then be able to
close its books on the case.
The report also proposes that the victim should have the same rights under
the Policyholders' Protection Act if the life company making the annuity
payments collapses.
The commission rejects giving power to the courts to order that damages be
paid in structured form. It says that the voluntary system should be
encouraged.
Structured Settlements and Interim and Provisional Damages. HMSO. Pounds
12.85.
</TEXT>
