<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Walker denies signing documents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, former head of the Brent Walker property and leisure
group, yesterday disputed prosecution claims he signed documents relating to
an associated company involved in the alleged fraudulent inflating of Brent
Walker profits.
Mr Walker, in his second day in the witness box at the Old Bailey, denied
that he had signed documents concerning Alberta, a joint venture involving
Brent Walker.
The prosecution alleges Alberta was used by Mr Walker to launder money to
disguise bogus film rights transactions that increased the profits of the
Brent Walker film division.
Mr Walker and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, the former Brent Walker finance director,
both deny charges of theft, fraudulent trading and conspiring to falsify the
company's accounts.
Questioned by his barrister, Mr Colin Nicholls QC, Mr Walker said he could
not be sure that he had signed some of the documents. He was unsure the
signatures looked like his, and one letter was on headed paper he would
never have used.
As chief executive of Brent Walker he signed so many documents he could not
read them and had to trust the senior executives responsible, he told the
court. 'Some weeks I got so tired my fingers could not hold the pen,' he
said.
Mr Walker also complained about the lack of support Brent Walker received
from the banks throughout its history. He was often asked to provide
security for loans from his personal assets. This, he said, was virtually
unheard of for public companies.
Mr Walker said flowcharts prepared by prosecutors from the Serious Fraud
Office concerning the alleged profits boosting made no sense to him. 'This
is an accountant's wonderland - an accountant's dreamland,' he said.
According to the charts, the banks concerned had never imposed any charges
for transferring large sums of money. This was never the case, said Mr
Walker.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
