<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / Saint Gobain chief indicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jean-Louis Beffa, head of the Saint Gobain glass group, was yesterday
charged with 'influence trafficking' by a French magistrate investigating
allegations that Pont-a-Mousson, a pipe-making subsidiary, paid a FFr4.4m
(Pounds 530,000) commission in 1988 to a Nantes politician to get a water
contract. After the announcement, Saint Gobain shares plummeted 4.2 per cent
in the hour before Paris trading closed. The investigating magistrate, Mr
Renaud van Ruymbeke, questioned Mr Beffa for five hours. Saint Gobain said:
'Considering that he had not got certain information from subsidiaries in
'the Nantes affair', Mr Ruymbeke thought it necessary to put the president
of the group under investigation.'
A company spokeswoman claimed that the magistrate had brought the accusation
to force more information out of the company and that the charge of
'influence trafficking' was chosen only because a political party was
involved. Mr Ruymbeke has been trying for a year to track the commission,
which is said to have reached a Republican party councillor in Nantes via
the Swiss bank account of a local industrialist. He has also been trying to
establish whether any of the money ended up with Mr Gerard Longuet, the
trade and industry minister, who presides over the Republican party and also
over the region of Lorraine where Pont-a-Mousson has its headquarters.
</TEXT>
