<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 94 / PM's patience runs out after 'secret deals' row at No 10
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday ordered Mr Ian Paisley to leave the Cabinet room
after the leader of the hardline Democratic Unionist party refused to accept
the prime minister's assurances on the Ulster peace process.
The confrontation happened as Mr Paisley, accompanied by the DUP's two other
MPs, tried to read a long statement condemning 'a concentrated attempt to
move us ratchet by ratchet out of the United Kingdom'.
Three times Mr Major interrupted Mr Paisley and demanded to know whether the
DUP leader accepted his word that no secret deals had been done with the
IRA.
When Mr Paisley declined to answer, the prime minister ended the meeting and
told the DUP delegation to leave.
The meeting was always likely to be theatrical, given the need for both Mr
Major and Mr Paisley to make their points, but it descended into farce when
Mr Paisley ignored the prime minister and insisted on delivering the rest of
his statement. As he read on, Mr Major left the room with Sir Patrick
Mayhew, Northern Ireland secretary, and Mr Michael Ancram, Northern Ireland
minister of state.
Outside Downing Street, Mr Paisley claimed the prime minister had shouted at
him as he tried to deliver his statement, and ended by ordering the DUP
delegation to 'get out of this room. Never come back until you're prepared
to say I speak the truth and do not tell lies.' Mr Paisley added: 'His
language was disgraceful. He thought that he would stir enmity in our
hearts, but the anger was in his heart. The shouting was on his part - we
remained silent and heard him out.'
British ministers and officials told a different story. Sir Patrick said Mr
Major 'saw no purpose whatsoever in answering questions that Mr Paisley had
put, or indeed any questions put by somebody who declined to accept the word
of the British prime minister'.
Mr Ancram said that Mr Major had been 'quiet and polite'. But he said the
prime minister would not meet Mr Paisley unless the DUP leader backed down.
'If there is to be another meeting, the same assurances will be required of
Mr Paisley,' Mr Ancram said. British officials said the prime minister
decided to take a stand over his government's integrity after Mr Paisley
accused him of lying in a broadcast interview.
Downing Street hopes the confrontation will reinforce the government's
credibility with moderate Northern Ireland unionists, whose support is
crucial to the peace process.
The brusque treatment of Mr Paisley is also designed to shore up support for
Mr James Molyneaux's Ulster Unionist party, which has so far gone along with
the government's approach.
Dr John Alderdice, leader of the non-sectarian Alliance party, praised Mr
Major for standing up to Mr Paisley. 'Previous British governments have
backed off and thought it better to appease the man, but Mr Major has simply
run out of patience,' he said.
Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, said he would welcome a meeting with
Mr Paisley.
</TEXT>
