<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Price rises help Coats to 10% advance: Textile group pays
its first foreign income dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coats Viyella, Britain's largest clothing and textiles company, yesterday
shrugged off patchy demand and sharp increases in raw material prices by
reporting a 10 per cent rise in first-half profits. The group's success in
passing on price rises to customers helped lift pre-tax profits from Pounds
62.8m to Pounds 69.2m in the six months to June 30.
'We've been more creative than other manufacturers in passing on increased
prices; we've recovered costs in the market place and we're on track to make
further progress,' said Mr Neville Bain, chief executive.
The group had seen signs of a strengthening recovery in the UK and
continental Europe, which contributed to increased sales of Pounds 1.22bn
(Pounds 1.17bn).
Operating profits, however, were held back by disappointing performances in
two core divisions - fashion retailing and clothing. Profits in the fashion
business fell from Pounds 4m to Pounds 3m after an unsuccessful attempt to
attract younger customers, while the clothing division reported reduced
gains of Pounds 3.3m (Pounds 5.2m) after closing its south Wales uniform
factory.
However, in the thread division - the largest business - profits rose
marginally from Pounds 45.9m to Pounds 46.1m and all other operations,
except home furnishings, improved.
The figures were also flattered by sharply reduced interest payments of
Pounds 14.2m (Pounds 26.1m) following the conversion last November of Pounds
97.7m worth of its 7.25 per cent convertible preference shares.
Mr Bain said the group would be paying a foreign income dividend (Fid) for
the first time. Under the scheme, introduced in the last Budget, companies
can relieve surplus advance corporation tax by paying dividends out of
overseas earnings. Coats declared a maiden Fid of 4.375p per share,
equivalent to a conventional dividend of 3.5p net - an 8 per cent increase.
Mr Bain admitted that the move had been prompted, in part, by market
criticism earlier this year of its third successive enhanced scrip dividend,
which contributed to a 15 per increase in the number of shares in issue.
Earnings per share, adjusted to treat the enhanced scrip dividends as rights
issues at less than the full market price, rose from a restated 4.6p to 6p.
Lex, Page 22; Market, Page 27
</TEXT>
<XX>
