   SYDNEY, TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Southcorp, the Australian packaging, wine and appliance manufacturer
formerly known as SA Brewing, yesterday announced a 2.4 per cent rise, to
ADollars 121.2m (USDollars 90.4m), in annual operating profits after tax but
before abnormals.
However, after abnormals, profits plunged 58.5 per cent to ADollars 49.8m.
The reason was a one-off charge of ADollars 68.7m, mainly related to
write-offs and restructuring costs at its troubled US water heater business.
Sales for the year were 1.6 per cent lower at ADollars 2.25bn.
Southcorp said that its packaging, wine and Australian appliance businesses
were 'very satisfactory'.
The wine business performed particularly well, in spite of competition in
the domestic market, with sales rising 11 per cent to ADollars 352m, and
pre-tax profits jumping 35 per cent to ADollars 62m.
However, the US water heater business incurred a USDollars 18.3m loss,
leading to a 20 per cent decline in pre-tax profits from the appliance
division.
