<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / UK Company News: ASW maintains interim despite fall to
Pounds 700,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ASW Holdings, the Cardiff-based steel products and construction systems
group, is maintaining its interim dividend of 3p a share in spite of a sharp
fall in first-half pre-tax profits from Pounds 1.5m to Pounds 700,000.
The decision is based on the expectation that trading conditions will
continue to improve following a much better second quarter in the company's
main steel business.
The company is also expecting the benefits from its investment and
cost-cutting programmes to come through.
Total turnover edged up from Pounds 230.5m to Pounds 237m, but profits from
continuing operations, excluding restructuring costs, fell from Pounds 5.2m
to Pounds 3.4m.
The steel side suffered a slide in profits from Pounds 7m to Pounds 4.1m. A
loss of Pounds 100,000 in the first quarter reflected the continuation of
the poor trading conditions experienced at the end of last year, but the
second quarter brought a significant recovery in selling prices and margins.
Prices continued firm and demand remained satisfactory, ASW said yesterday.
An Pounds 11m-Pounds 12m upgrade of the Cardiff bar and section mill has
been carried out, which ASW said would achieve substantial cost reductions
when it came into full operation next year. Meanwhile, as a result of this
and other restructuring to be undertaken in the second half, there would be
exceptional restructuring costs estimated at Pounds 3.5m this year, due
mainly to redundancies. Some Pounds 600,000 of this was incurred in the
first half.
The construction systems business showed some improvement, helped by the
restructuring carried out at the end of last year, reducing its first-half
loss from Pounds 1.8m to Pounds 700,000. The company reiterated that the
business would be profitable in the second half.
The group's net borrowings stood at Pounds 43.4m on June 30, only slightly
up from Pounds 42.8m a year earlier despite a rise in capital spending from
Pounds 3.4m to Pounds 10.2m.
Net profit rose from Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 1.6m following the release of
an earlier provision related to the tax treatment of the takeover of
Manchester Steel in 1985. A favourable agreement with the Inland Revenue was
reached early this year.
After payment of preference and ordinary dividends, the retained loss for
the period was reduced from Pounds 2m a year earlier to Pounds 1.1m. Basic
earnings per share were 1.3p (0.0p).
</TEXT>
